		<div class="entry-content"><div class="w592"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/08/09/nyregion/20150908PRAIRIEss-slide-PG3Y-LN/20150908PRAIRIEss-slide-PG3Y-tmagArticle.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/08/09/nyregion/20150908PRAIRIEss-slide-PG3Y-LN/20150908PRAIRIEss-slide-PG3Y-tmagArticle.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/08/09/nyregion/20150908PRAIRIEss-slide-PG3Y-LN/20150908PRAIRIEss-slide-PG3Y-tmagArticle.jpg" id="100000003878648" width="592" height="395" alt="Vaughn Minott, 17, from Queens, watching a herd of bison from the back of a pickup truck out on the open landscape of the American Prairie Reserve in Montana. Of the experience, he said, &lt;em&gt;â&lt;/em&gt;It was like that once-in-a-lifetime moment.&lt;em&gt;â&lt;/em&gt; &lt;a href=&quot;//www.nytimes.com/2015/08/09/nyregion/from-skyscrapers-to-big-sky.html&quot;&gt;Related Article&lt;/a&gt;"   /><meta itemprop="height" content="395"><meta itemprop="width" content="592"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">Vaughn Minott, 17, from Queens, watching a herd of bison from the back of a pickup truck out on the open landscape of the American Prairie Reserve in Montana. Of the experience, he said, <em>â</em>It was like that once-in-a-lifetime moment.<em>â</em> <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/08/09/nyregion/from-skyscrapers-to-big-sky.html">Related Article</a></span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Lido Vizzutti for The New York Times</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="//learning.blogs.nytimes.com/2015/09/04/teenagers-in-the-times-august-2015/" data-title="Teenagers in The Times | August 2015" data-description="A roundup of all the articles about young people that appeared in The New York Times in August.">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">We present the August edition of Teens in The Times, a <a href="//learning.blogs.nytimes.com/category/teens-in-the-times/">monthly feature</a> that rounds up recent articles about young people that have appeared in The Times.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span id="more-161165"></span></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">As summer winds down and the new school year begins, teenagers made headlines in myriad arenas, including the pool, where Katie Ledecky broke record after record, and the tennis court, where Victoria Duval returned to competition following a bout with cancer. Others used the season for enrichment, whether via taking online courses, leaving the city to explore the prairie, or&#8230;<a href="//www.nytimes.com/politics/first-draft/2015/08/20/deez-nuts-for-president-why-not-says-iowa-farm-boy/">running for president</a>.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Where will September take teenagers? Tune in on the first Friday in October and find out.    </p>
<hr />
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Civics, Politics, Government, Economics and Business</strong></p>
<div class="w75 left"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/08/30/world/30MEXICOOPIUM1/30MEXICOOPIUM1-thumbStandard.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/08/30/world/30MEXICOOPIUM1/30MEXICOOPIUM1-thumbStandard.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/08/30/world/30MEXICOOPIUM1/30MEXICOOPIUM1-thumbStandard.jpg" id="100000003880258" width="75" height="75" alt="A woman with a child worked in a poppy field in Guerrero State in Mexico. As American heroin use has risen sharply, so has opium production south of the border."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="75"><meta itemprop="width" content="75"></div></figure></div><p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">
<a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/08/30/world/americas/mexican-opium-production-rises-to-meet-heroin-demand-in-us.html">Young Hands in Mexico Feed Growing U.S. Demand for Heroin</a><br />
<em>To meet the U.S. demand for heroin, Mexico is enlisting children to harvest opium. The money is too much to ignore for most, and the terrain is more manageable for those of slighter frame.</em></p>
<div class="w75 left"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/08/20/us/politics/20firstdraft-deeznuts/20firstdraft-deeznuts-thumbStandard.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/08/20/us/politics/20firstdraft-deeznuts/20firstdraft-deeznuts-thumbStandard.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/08/20/us/politics/20firstdraft-deeznuts/20firstdraft-deeznuts-thumbStandard.jpg" id="100000003866553" width="75" height="75" alt="Campaign buttons. A 15-year-old about to start his sophomore year in high school has registered his candidacy for president withÂ the Federal Election Commission. He hopes, he said, to &quot;clear the way for a future third-party movement.ââ"   /><meta itemprop="height" content="75"><meta itemprop="width" content="75"></div></figure></div><p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">
<a href="//www.nytimes.com/politics/first-draft/2015/08/20/deez-nuts-for-president-why-not-says-iowa-farm-boy/">Deez Nuts for President? Why Not, Says Iowa Farm Boy</a><br />
<em>Supporters who picked up the Deez Nuts meme tweeted to Public Policy Polling, a nonscientific polling operation, asking it to add him to its surveys, and it did. In head-to-head match-ups with Donald J. Trump and Hillary Rodham Clinton, Deez Nuts, 15, drew 8 percent in Minnesota and 7 percent in Iowa.</em></p>
<div class="w75 left"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/08/02/world/02palestinians-web/02palestinians-web-thumbStandard.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/08/02/world/02palestinians-web/02palestinians-web-thumbStandard.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/08/02/world/02palestinians-web/02palestinians-web-thumbStandard.jpg" id="100000003832201" width="75" height="75" alt="Laith al-Khaldi who was shot of Friday during a demonstration near Ramallah, died on Saturday."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="75"><meta itemprop="width" content="75"></div></figure></div><p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">
<a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/08/02/world/middleeast/palestinian-teenager-is-fatally-shot-while-protesting-deadly-arson-attack.html">Censure and Clashes After West Bank Attack</a><br />
<em>Laith al-Khaldi, 17, was the sixth Palestinian to be fatally shot by Israeli security forces in recent weeks.<br />
