<div class="w75 left"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/08/06/world/americas/20150807-CUBA-slide-7DND/20150807-CUBA-slide-7DND-thumbStandard.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/08/06/world/americas/20150807-CUBA-slide-7DND/20150807-CUBA-slide-7DND-thumbStandard.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/08/06/world/americas/20150807-CUBA-slide-7DND/20150807-CUBA-slide-7DND-thumbStandard.jpg" id="100000003839393" width="75" height="75" alt=""   /><meta itemprop="height" content="75"><meta itemprop="width" content="75"></div></figure></div><p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">
<a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/08/07/world/americas/cuban-youth-see-new-us-embassy-but-same-old-drab-life.html">Cuban Youth See New U.S. Embassy, but Same Old Drab Life</a><br />
<em>As much as the young welcome political opening and economic reform, such changes are unlikely to filter down to their lives anytime soon.  </em></p>
<div class="w75 left"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/08/12/us/MISSISSIPPI/MISSISSIPPI-thumbStandard.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/08/12/us/MISSISSIPPI/MISSISSIPPI-thumbStandard.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/08/12/us/MISSISSIPPI/MISSISSIPPI-thumbStandard.jpg" id="100000003848631" width="75" height="75" alt="Jaelyn Young and Muhammad Dakhlalla."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="75"><meta itemprop="width" content="75"></div></figure></div><p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">
<a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/08/12/us/newlyweds-are-accused-of-planning-to-join-isis.html">Newlyweds Are Accused of Planning to Join ISIS</a><br />
<em>The couple, Jaelyn Delshaun Young, 19, and Muhammad Oda Dakhlalla, 22, unwittingly made travel plans with undercover federal agents on social media that included discussing a trip to Syria via Greece and Turkey as a honeymoon ruse.  </em></p>
<div class="w75 left"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/08/04/world/05BROTHERHOOD-1/05BROTHERHOOD-1-thumbStandard.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/08/04/world/05BROTHERHOOD-1/05BROTHERHOOD-1-thumbStandard.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/08/04/world/05BROTHERHOOD-1/05BROTHERHOOD-1-thumbStandard.jpg" id="100000003834440" width="75" height="75" alt="Members of the Muslim Brotherhood were held in a cage during a trial in Cairo in May."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="75"><meta itemprop="width" content="75"></div></figure></div><p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">
<a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/08/06/world/middleeast/younger-muslim-brotherhood-members-in-egypt-bridle-at-nonviolent-stance.html">Push for Retribution in Egypt Frays Muslim Brotherhood</a><br />
<em>A veteran leader of the Muslim Brotherhood was so alarmed by the rising calls for violence from the groupâs youth that he risked arrest to urge the movement to stay peaceful.</em></p>
<div class="w75 left"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/08/13/world/middleeast/20150813-ISISSLAVE-slide-CON6/20150813-ISISSLAVE-slide-CON6-thumbStandard.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/08/13/world/middleeast/20150813-ISISSLAVE-slide-CON6/20150813-ISISSLAVE-slide-CON6-thumbStandard.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/08/13/world/middleeast/20150813-ISISSLAVE-slide-CON6/20150813-ISISSLAVE-slide-CON6-thumbStandard.jpg" id="100000003848066" width="75" height="75" alt="A 12-year-old girl in the Kurdistan region of northern Iraq."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="75"><meta itemprop="width" content="75"></div></figure></div><p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">
<a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/08/14/world/middleeast/isis-enshrines-a-theology-of-rape.html">ISIS Enshrines a Theology of Rape</a><br />
<em>Interviews with 21 women and girls who recently escaped the Islamic State, as well as an examination of the groupâs official communications, illuminate how the practice has been incorporated in the groupâs core tenets. </em></p>
<div class="w75 left"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/08/08/world/NORWAY1/NORWAY1-thumbStandard.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/08/08/world/NORWAY1/NORWAY1-thumbStandard.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/08/08/world/NORWAY1/NORWAY1-thumbStandard.jpg" id="100000003843184" width="75" height="75" alt="Mani Hussaini, left, leader of the Workersâ Youth League, with Anniken Huitfeldt, a member of Norwayâs Parliament, and Secretary General Jens Stoltenberg of NATO at the camp on Friday."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="75"><meta itemprop="width" content="75"></div></figure></div><p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">
<a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/08/08/world/europe/norway-utoya-breivik-camp.html">Norwegian Youths Return to Camp on Utoya, the Site of a 2011 Massacre</a><br />
<em>More than 1,000 Norwegian youths joined the secretary general of NATO and other dignitaries on the island of Utoya, reclaiming the bucolic summer retreat from the horrors of a 2011 attack by a right-wing extremist that killed 69 people.   </em></p>
<div class="w75 left"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/08/11/world/10Pakistan-web/10Pakistan-web-thumbStandard.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/08/11/world/10Pakistan-web/10Pakistan-web-thumbStandard.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/08/11/world/10Pakistan-web/10Pakistan-web-thumbStandard.jpg" id="100000003845399" width="75" height="75" alt="Children who are said to have been abused hid their faces while their mothers were interviewed by a journalist in their village in Punjab Province on Sunday."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="75"><meta itemprop="width" content="75"></div></figure></div><p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">
