<em>A look into the world of three teenage girls who abandoned their lives in London to join the Islamic State.</em></p>
<div class="w75 left"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/08/23/nyregion/23UNACCOMPANIED1/23UNACCOMPANIED1-thumbStandard-v2.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/08/23/nyregion/23UNACCOMPANIED1/23UNACCOMPANIED1-thumbStandard-v2.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/08/23/nyregion/23UNACCOMPANIED1/23UNACCOMPANIED1-thumbStandard-v2.jpg" id="100000003869209" width="75" height="75" alt="Brayan, 16, at the Central American Refugee Center in Hempstead, N.Y. Brayan fled El Salvador and entered the United States last year."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="75"><meta itemprop="width" content="75"></div></figure></div><p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">
<a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/08/24/nyregion/border-crisis-shifts-as-undocumented-childrens-cases-overwhelm-courts.html">Immigration Crisis Shifts From Border to Courts</a><br />
<em>The number of children arriving at the Mexican border has sharply decreased in the past year, but the crisis has shifted. not ended. It is playing out in courtrooms crowded with young defendants but lacking lawyers and judges to handle the sheer volume of cases. </em></p>
<div class="w75 left"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/08/19/us/19stpauls-subjp1-LN/19stpauls-subjp1-thumbStandard.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/08/19/us/19stpauls-subjp1-LN/19stpauls-subjp1-thumbStandard.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/08/19/us/19stpauls-subjp1-LN/19stpauls-subjp1-thumbStandard.jpg" id="100000003865657" width="75" height="75" alt="Owen Labrie, 19, has pleaded not guilty to 10 counts, including felonious sexual assault, in connection with an encounter with a 15-year-old girl at St. Paulâs School last year. &lt;a href=&quot;//www.nytimes.com/2015/08/19/us/rape-case-explores-culture-of-elite-st-pauls-school.html&quot;&gt;Related Article&lt;/a&gt;"   /><meta itemprop="height" content="75"><meta itemprop="width" content="75"></div></figure></div><p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">
